Herrett told me that she had reached a better understanding of what her staff thought and felt in the three years she had used Glint.
In addition to the rapid surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a warm card to the company and shows in visual form which units have more complaints and which managers have a low validation rating that allows them to understand why.
Companies realize little that they need to control the workplace, otherwise they will become another Uber, who was involved in a scandal when a former staff member published a post on a blog describing an aggressive environment in which those who complained were punished.
For startups like "Glint", it's a desire to control the situation - the opportunity for a profitable business.
According to the Internet portal “Let's talk about payments” devoted to financial technology, the global governance, regulation and conformity industry may cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
Convercent startup from Denver, Colorado, which helps companies to prevent and detect misconduct, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year in the face of a fall in Hubert's reputation.
Convercent has almost 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tella.
The Uber has recently appeared among clients.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send individual-ordered staff surveys, collect confidential responses in real time and monitor thermal maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows staff to report misconduct.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go straight to the head office.
“The court of public opinion has seized the authority of the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinn, founder and president of Convercent.
If it is found that the company has been mistreated or has acted immorally, even if the inspectors do not intervene, the company may have costly consequences in the form of boycotts on the part of clients, staff outflows and lawsuits, Quinn reported.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees in 500 facilities, has been using Convercent for over a year to ensure that staff are aware of the rules and procedures and to offer an easy way to approach the company's head office.
In the past, if the staff member wanted to report the problem, he or she had to look for the phone number or Mail of the head office, file an official complaint and hope that she or she would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and awkward experience, said James Vitrano, director of the legal office of Ruby Tuesday, that there was no normal way to monitor staff complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states — such as discrimination, harassation and unfair pay — can be discovered and addressed more quickly.
