According to Queensland, companies began to take more seriously the ethics, values and involvement of staff members in 2002, after Arthur Andersen failed due to ethical irregularities resulting from Dela Enron.
But it was only when social networks were spread that companies realized they couldn't keep their dirty laundry from spreading virus on the network.
“Before we start using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both the “Glint” and the “Convercent” offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee for the use of their products.
This is a business model and an opportunity that was approved by venture investors who supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company's total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
