If change does not take place fast enough, or at all, frustration may develop and staff will lose interest.
“If you are going to ask for 4,000 proposals, you should be ready to hold 4,000 interviews,” says Russell Rat, president of the management consulting firm Kotter International, who had to see companies make a mistake, relying too much on data collection.
'Because if you don't go to the end, the staff will say, 'Did you really hear me?
Don't you care?
And if you don't care, why don't I care?"
According to Herrett, Madison Red, which now conducts monthly staff surveys, is able to take action on the same day that someone reports the problem with Glint.
