Create a novel comic book: One castle in English history
In the recent past, Scotty's tiny castle was filmed in the music video "Squeeze", and in the 1970s and 1980s served as a haven for Margaret Tatcher.
But for 700 years from his comfortable place in the Byul Valley in Kent County, he was watching a ferocious story around him, and now he inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshire, with a rough hair and history, on a comic book.
"I think it's so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago," he said with encouragement.
"You feel that way when you hold this letter in your hand."
The Castle in England covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Evardian Era and tells of families who lived in Scotty; each story is illustrated by one of the young British artists, Isaac Lenkewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first book, which is based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote "The Dyings of the Dead and Other History" -- a collection of British Library records; this project suddenly touched him to the depths of his soul.
"I could have been touched by just a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the cocoa," he says.
"It's his fingerprint."
And letters always smell smoke, because in those days fire was lit.
And 300 years later, in the future, you feel like you're there too.
Oh, how I love archives!"
For a person who is so passionate about old papers, getting support from the National Foundation and the English Arts Council and living in the castle for four months (the truth is, I've gone a little bit too far) seems too good to be true.
Rhodes studied the Victorian Castle for days, walked through the archives and considered many treasures of name and old things - for example, the hyenas' heads on the walls or bottles that had been in the ditch for centuries.
He went through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talked to the forestmen, gardeners, and sometimes to the artists who worked on illustrations of his book.
Then at night, he was "drinking whiskey and sitting down to write."
The history of Scotty's castle was not well understood, because the National Foundation had full access to it only in 2006 when the last heir, Elizabeth Hassy, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff were just starting to deal with an archive that he described as "that aristocrats have been dropping on the attic for centuries."
The days, the letters of the British Empire, the maps showing who owned what they were saying, "You think land disputes are boring," says Rhodes, "but that's what two families were fighting for.
That's the way it is, guys!"
In some stories, the castle is becoming the starting point for broader research in English history: for example, in "Worker's", the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the 1381 Cristian Revolution.
“There is evidence of the rebellion that took place in the castle in 1380 in a book called “Kenta and Sassex families of Russia”, says Rhodes.
"The peasant rebellion started in these places, and I thought that rebellion was the right beginning.
Maybe they were connected?"
Other stories are closely related to the history of the castle, such as "The Priest", which tells of a Jesuit priest whom the Darrell family had hidden in their home for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "Smuggler," about the 18th-century smugglers Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by stoning the tomb (which was discovered a few years later when the tomb was dug).
The Darrells are Rods' beloved family of all those who lived in Scotty, "The gentlemen seemed to be perfect, they were always in debt, and they spent money on things they couldn't afford.
The Darrell men have dealt with their debt problems by marrying rich older women, and I think of them as a company of pretty guys who can look after the great estates."
After the end of work, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to gain unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in a Finnish silence where he wrote a graphic novel about Eliamyak, a place where there was a sanatorium at the beginning of the 20th century and then it grew again with a forest.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he said.
"I felt like this: God damn it, I have to go back into real life."
