Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can help to ease the OVC.
Red meat and chocolate are commonly considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies suggest the opposite: A diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help to ease the symptoms of intestinal inflammation.
This incurable disease, which affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, leads to cripples and stomach swelling, chronic or bloody weariness, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
While meat and dairy products are usually recommended to alleviate symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid of the protein tryptofan contributes to the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
The leading researcher, Dr. Marco Colónna, explained that intestinal immune cells ensure that harmful microbes from food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of starting an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance while protecting the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
If the balance is too severe for inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory intestinal diseases.
The experiments showed that mice with certain bacteria in their intestines are developing cell tolerance.
And this bacteria needs a tryptofan -- one of the building blocks of a protein -- to start these cells.
Professor Colonna said, "We've established a connection between one type of bacteria, Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of the normal intestinal microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more triptofane was contained in mice' diet, the more immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same would work for people: a combination of L. reuteri and triptofan-rich diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the intestine.
Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganvas, after studying the variety of immune cell tolerance, found that one group of test mice had these cells, and another group that belonged to the same line but was held separately, did not.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by intestinal microbioms of mice, bacteria, viruses and fungi, which usually live in the stomach tract.
The DNA of the intestine cells of mice has been segregated and six types of bacteria present in mice that have immune cells but are missing from mice that do not have them have them have been detected.
Muscles grown in a sterile environment that did not have good microbioms and did not develop this type of immune cell have L. reuteri, and they have immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers raised L. reuteri in the liquid environment and then transferred small amounts of fluid - without bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells released from mice.
Immune cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of triptofane processing known as indol-3-milic acid.
