The White House report cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to records from the military forces provided by the magazine TIME, the White House's decision last month to push a Marine Helicopter into the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers $24,000.
The white and green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as Martin One, when the president is on board, became a central element of the 17 July White House event showing American construction programmes.
President Donald Trump, Vice-President Mike Pens and top officials of the White House examined technological products from all 50 states.
A helicopter in Connecticut was displayed next to a boat from the state of Man, a fire truck from Visconsin, and a vehicle from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter (HMX-1), the unit responsible for managing the helicopter, the White House Military Administration ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or FRAGO, only 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of the “unusual” event.
“I just wanted you to know that you are aware because it is an unusually widely publicized press event”, wrote the HMX-1 commander in an e-mail to his superior, the first Deputy Chief of Aviation of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on 17 July to attend an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and remain there until the lawn is released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required to return the flight in accordance with the working hours restrictions.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the unit ' s guards remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was not clear from the records received by the “TIME” magazine whether the second crew was required as a result.
The Hetch Act prohibits federal employees from using State property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event was in conflict with the regulation.
“We asked, among other things, whether it was a violation of Hatch’s law, and we were told that it was not,” the commander wrote.
“It looks like you have nowhere to go”, the deputy said.
The event “Make in America” was declared an official event by the White House and was not covered by the Hetch Act.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance the health-care reform that was then under way in the Senate and commended efforts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is hardly new.
The presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it's unusual to ask for them only in the interest of photography.
Trump had already been discussed in February, when the presidential plane had gone backwards during its first pre-election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and its Twitter account had been overwhelmed by complaints about the use of the presidential plane by its predecessor.
“White house in awe of the American screening of products from 50 states made by American American workers from American materials”, said Linda Walters, Deputy Spokesperson for the White House.
HMX-1 crews often take training flights around Washington Agglomeration and South Lawn to train the U.S. President's transportation to the White House with accuracy to an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training sessions at the White House.
According to an official, the flight carried out for the “Action in America” event was counted to the crew on the basis of the required training flights per month.
The unit ' s helicopters on that day also flew 11 additional hours as part of “non-presidential support tasks”.
According to the White House, taxpayers were not charged with any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of Sikorsky reported that the company had not participated in a demonstration of the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not account for the presidential flight budget and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Ministry of Defence temporary rates for fiscal year 2017, the rate of reimbursement of the Ministry of Defence for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit records 30 minutes of aircraft in the air each way from its airfield based on the Quantico Marine Aeronautics Base in Virginia.
The White House states that the real cost of using the helicopter is much lower than that rate.
“To calculate the value of taxpayers based on an estimated rate of reimbursement is totally wrong,” says Walters.
“These indicative rates include personnel, services and many other irreversible costs, which are included in the annual appropriations.”
According to a study carried out in 2015 by RENDC, rates of reimbursement do not include the cost of personnel, but do take into account the cost of fuel, services and expenses specified in the contract.
At the time, the former White House spokesman, Sean Spyser, spoke out to defend the use of the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to demonstrate this week things done in America,” Spice said.
“I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of their contribution to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we're all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment, which has been worked on by so many Americans.
It is, of course, appropriate to draw attention to this.”
It was not clear if Trump was interacting with a helicopter while watching the South Lawn during the event, but he was definitely sitting in the driver's seat in a fire car.
Inside the White House Trump addressed representatives of Sikorsky, joking the press about his own fleet of company products.
“I know "Sikorsky very well," said the President. “I have three of them.”
